Approximately 60 percent of milk traders are abiding by hygiene guidelines set up by the Kenya Dairy Board.Chief inspector Evans Mwangi yesterday attributed the rise in compliance to training and awareness campaigns the board has conducted. Mwangi said the dairy board inspects milk vendors and identifies gaps that need to be addressed. He spoke at Ruiru town in Nairobi after a two-day workshop with the vendors.Mwangi said KDB will enforce the Dairy Industry Act in improving sales. We are here to provide advice on hygienic practises and sale of safe milk, he said. Mwangi said vendors are trained on the level of compliance and running a successful business.The dairy board and Kenya Market Trust signed a deal in August on quality assurance.